ions, its limits and its risks, its history and its possibilities. The book is a journey through a landscape of ideas, images, and texts from diverse sources—theological, psychological, etymological, and artistic, but mainly across the history of philosophy, from Plato and Saint Augustine, through Kant and Hegel, Marx and Heidegger, up to contemporary critical theory. Along the way, Ben-Shai invites the reader to examine their own orientation of thought, even at the moment of reading the book; to question popular discourse; and to revisit the philosophical canon, revealing affinities among often antagonistic traditions, such as Catholicism and Marxism. Most importantly, Critique of Critique sets the ground for an examination of alternative orientations of critical thinking, other ways of inhabiting and grasping the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCritical thinking. 0aCriticism (Philosophy) 0aCriticism (Philosophy). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAuthority.  aConfession.  aCritical thinking.  aCritique.  aEnlightenment.  aHistory of philosophy.  aOntology.  aOrientations.  aPower.  aProgress.  aRevolution.  aSpectacle.1 aKottman, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363383440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633834423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633834/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles